ubed</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Fried Onions : 250 grams</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Ginger Garlic Paste : 1 tablespoon</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Yogurt : 4 tablespoons</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Coconut Powder : 4 tablespoons</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Raw Papaya : 2 tablespoons</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Green Chilies : 4</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Oil : As required</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Strong Thread or String : As required</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Masala : 1 packet (50 grams)</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Method</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Mix the beef with fried onions, ginger garlic paste, coconut powder, green chilies, raw papaya, and Korma Masala.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Grind everything finely, fold in the yogurt, and knead into a well-blended mix.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Leave the mince to rest for an hour.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Press handfuls of the mince onto skewers, wrap securely with string and barbecue over hot coals.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Frequently brush or sprinkle with oil, turn skewers carefully to ensure kababs remain intact.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>When cooked through, serve with fresh salad and raita.</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\nLike the tarka aloo, this dish is also an indoor meal of sorts. However, as this is a heavy meal, this suits best as a side to the main course alongside Polao, biriyani or Kacchi.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4><strong> Afghani Pulao</strong></h4>\r\n<em><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-668 size-large\" src=\"https://ayojok.com/ideas-and-stories/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/image005-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"An Unconventional Dish for indoor wedding events\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" />This recipe is a delectable marriage between the self-effacing khichuri and the extravagant pulao with the amalgamation of daal.</em>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-672\" src=\"https://ayojok.com/ideas-and-stories/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Veg_Handi_1600-737x1024.jpg\" alt=\"An Unconventional Dish for indoor wedding events\" width=\"640\" height=\"889\" />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Ingredients</em></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><em>Rice : 3 cups</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Oil : 1 cup</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Onion (sliced) : 2 medium</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Mutton : 750 gm</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>National Ginger &amp; Garlic Paste : 1 tablespoon each</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Pulao Masala : 1/2 packet</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Carrots (grated) : 1 cup</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Raisins : 2 tablespoons</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Sugar : 2 tablespoons</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Almonds (blanched) : 10</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Pistachios (blanched) : 10</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><em>Method</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Wash and soak rice for at least 3 hours and keep changing the water every hour.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>In a large pot, fry the onions till dark brown in color. Strain, crush and keep aside.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>In the same oil add the mutton, National Ginger Paste, and National Garlic Paste. Cook until the meat is slightly brown.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Now add Pulao Masala and 6-7 cups of water; bring to a full boil then turn the heat low and simmer till the meat is tender. If required add Iodized Salt to taste.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>In a small saucepan add carrots, raisins, sugar and 1/2 cup water. Cook on medium heat until the carrots get softened and liquid dries out. Keep aside.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Add crushed fried onions to the mutton gravy that depart a deep caramel flavor and color to the gravy.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>When the meat is ready, strain the soaked rice and add to the meat. Cook over a high heat until most of the liquid disappears. You should have enough liquid left to cook rice in. You may add some additional hot water if required.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Turn the heat low.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Serve the pulao with the carrots, and raisins. Generously garnish with blanched almonds and pistachios.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis delicious and extravagant dish is an all-event-purpose dish, however, Afghani pulao tastes best when cooked slow and served hot. We recommend you to make this dish during Aakhd or Mehedi nights with a fewer number of guests as catering this pulao is a complex process and it will require a lot of labor and time to serve a greater number of guests.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4><strong>Fried Chops Recipe</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-669 size-large\" src=\"https://ayojok.com/ideas-and-stories/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/image007-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" />Typical chops made special with a unique frying method which will give you a scrumptious meal.</em></p>\r\n<strong><em>Ingredients</em></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><em>chops : 1 kg</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Onions : 2</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Ginger Garlic Paste : 2 teaspoon</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Vinegar : half cup</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Eggs : 2</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Breadcrumbs : 1 cup</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Oil For frying</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Masala : 1 packet (50 grams)</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Method</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<em>In a deep pot, combine the onions, chops, ginger garlic paste, Masala, vinegar and 2 glasses of water.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Set on medium heat to cook.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>When the chops are tender, remove them from the pot and let cool.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Dip the cooled chops first in beaten egg, then in breadcrumbs and deep fry to a crispy golden color.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Drain on absorbent paper and serve hot.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFried Chops are comparatively easy to cook and serve, but it is absolutely necessary that they are freshly fried. Having them fried 2-3 hours before serving will deteriorate its taste and make it look unappealing. Traditionally fried chops are an essential fine-dine menu in Pakistan during the wedding, but we recommend this dish for Aakhd during the winter season.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Reference: <a href=\"http://www.madeeasy.com.pk\">www.madeeasy.com.pk</a></em>\r\n\r\n<em>\r\n**</em>Image taken from pinterest', 'An Unconventional Dish for indoor wedding events', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '578-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-01-03 11:30:39', '2019-01-03 11:30:39', '', 578, 'https://ayojok.com/ideas-and-stories/2019/01/03/578-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
